headline_main: Donald Trump Wishes He Were Running Against Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez
headline_print_headline: Trump Wishes His Opponent Were A.O.C.

abstract: Second-quarter totals show a lower tier of candidates burning through cash trying to stay viable, while the leaders banked millions. Who has more than 300 people on her payroll?
snippet: Second-quarter totals show a lower tier of candidates burning through cash trying to stay viable, while the leaders banked millions. Who has more than 300 people on her payroll?
lead_paragraph: Mayor Pete Buttigieg soared and Senator Elizabeth Warren surged. Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. was solid. Senator Bernie Sanders held steady. Senator Kamala Harris scored late.

abstract: The dog whistle days are apparently over.
snippet: The dog whistle days are apparently over.
lead_paragraph: In 1981 Lee Atwater, the famed Republican political operative, explained to an interviewer how his party had learned to exploit racial antagonism using dog whistles. “You start out in 1954 by saying ‘Nigger, nigger, nigger.’” But by the late 1960s, “that hurts you, backfires. So you say stuff like, uh, ‘forced busing,’ ‘states’ rights,’ and all that stuff, and you’re getting so abstract. Now, you’re talking about cutting taxes, and all these things you’re talking about are totally economic things and a byproduct of them is, blacks get hurt worse than whites.”

abstract: Mr. Biden, detailing his health care plan in Iowa, paraphrased a notorious promise made by Mr. Obama: “If you like your private insurance, you can keep it.”
snippet: Mr. Biden, detailing his health care plan in Iowa, paraphrased a notorious promise made by Mr. Obama: “If you like your private insurance, you can keep it.”
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — It was the singular promise that doomed the public perception of President Barack Obama’s health care law — and now former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. is using it on the campaign trail.
